-0.020615629851818085, 0.04020991176366806, 0.01865065097808838, 0.00615582475438714, 0.010435482487082481, 0.00587828503921628, 0.03823383152484894, 0.005778370890766382, 0.025689050555229187, -0.02382398582994938, -0.0013308016350492835, -0.01744057796895504, -0.02155926264822483, -0.0023382697254419327, -0.024823127314448357, 0.044894780963659286, 0.0020981980487704277, 0.02846444398164749, -0.009736083447933197, -0.028753085061907768, 0.03314930945634842, -0.023624157533049583, 0.007843264378607273, 0.014243324287235737, 0.008709187619388103, 0.015297973528504372, -0.042208198457956314, -0.015120348893105984, 0.010529845952987671, 0.0023854514583945274, 0.03281626105308533, 0.011856485158205032, -0.013377401046454906, -0.015508904121816158, -0.01970529928803444, 0.011423523537814617, 0.011084925383329391, -0.0038133917842060328, -0.032016947865486145, 0.022847047075629234, -0.022158749401569366, 0.03670181334018707, -0.022513998672366142, -0.026466161012649536, 0.054841794073581696, -0.027642928063869476, 0.020771050825715065, -0.011656655929982662]], "input": ["\"STRUCTURE IN DATA ANALYTICS\":\"Structure refers to the organization of data. Much big data is unstructured, requiring more complex and time-consuming techniques to analyze effectively.\"", "\"RELIABILITY IN DATA ANALYTICS\":\"Reliability refers to the degree of trustworthiness of data. Different data sources have varying degrees of reliability, and understanding why certain data differs significantly can provide valuable insights.\"", "\"PRIORITISATION IN DATA ANALYTICS\":\"Prioritisation in data analytics involves determining which insights are the most significant and relevant for decision-making. Different types of data may provide contradictory indications, and it is crucial to identify which data best indicates short-term and long-term trends.\"", "\"CLARITY IN DATA ANALYTICS\":\"Clarity in data analytics refers to the ability to interpret and understand the data clearly. Qualitative insights may be difficult to translate into quantitative effects, and there is a risk of relying on data that provides a clear picture rather than the most significant data.\"", "\"FLEXED BUDGET PREPARATION FOR COWLY RESTAURANT\":\"Yumi Co's Cowly restaurant's budget preparation involves comparing actual performance against budgeted figures. The flexed budget adjusts the original budget based on the actual number of customers, providing a more accurate comparison of revenue and costs.\"", "\"DETAILED VARIANCE ANALYSIS FOR PORTLAND CO'S PRODUCT\":\"Portland Co manufactures a product from a standard grade of material. The case involves calculating various variances such as sales volume variance, sales price variance, materials price variance, materials usage variance, labour rate variance, labour efficiency variance, variable overhead rate variance, variable overhead efficiency variance, and fixed overhead expenditure variance based on the actual and budgeted production and sales data.\"", "\"VARIANCE ANALYSIS AND FLEXIBLE BUDGETING FOR MERMUS CO\":\"Mermus Co is comparing budget and actual data for the last three months. The company uses standard costing and absorbs fixed production overheads on a machine hour basis. The case involves preparing a revised budget using a flexible budgeting approach and calculating various variances including raw material total cost variance, direct labour total cost variance, fixed overhead efficiency variance, fixed overhead capacity variance, and fixed overhead expenditure variance.\"", "\"OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\":", "\"RAW MATERIALS COST VARIANCE\":\"The budgeted raw material cost for production of 95,000 units was $1.40 per unit (133,000/95,000) but the actual raw material cost for production of 90,000 units was $1.45 per unit (130,500/90,000). The raw material cost per unit may have increased either because more raw materials per unit were used than budgeted, or because the price per unit of raw material was higher than budgeted.\"", "\"FIXED OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY VARIANCE EXPLANATION\":\"The fixed overhead efficiency variance measures the extent to which more or less standard hours were used for the actual production than budgeted. In this case, a total of 27,200 machine hours were actually used, when only 27,000 standard machine hours should have been used. The difference may be due to poorer production planning than expected or to machine breakdowns.\"", "\"FIXED OVERHEAD EXPENDITURE VARIANCE EXPLANATION\":\"The fixed overhead expenditure variance measures the extent to which budgeted fixed overhead differs from actual fixed overhead. Here, actual fixed overhead is $10,100 less than budgeted. This could be due to an error in forecasting fixed production overheads such as rent and power costs, or to a decrease in fixed production overheads, such as changing to a cheaper cleaning contractor.\"", "\"PURPOSES OF A BUDGETING SYSTEM\":\"Key purposes of a budgeting system include planning, co-ordination, communication, control, motivation, and performance evaluation.\"", "\"PLANNING IN BUDGETING\":\"One of the key purposes of a budgeting system is to require planning to occur. Strategic planning covers several years but a budget represents a financial plan covering a shorter period (i.e. a budget is an operational plan). Planning helps an organisation to anticipate key changes in the business environment that could potentially impact on business activities and to prepare appropriate responses. Planning also ensures that the budgeted activities of the organisation will support the achievement of the organisation's objectives.\"", "\"CO-ORDINATION IN BUDGETING\":\"Many organisations undertake a number of activities, which need to be co-ordinated, if the organisation is to meet its objectives. The budgeting system facilitates this co-ordination since organisational activities and the links between them are thoroughly investigated during budget preparation, and the overall coherence between the budgeted activities is reviewed before senior managers agree the master budget. Without the framework of the budgeting system, individual managers may be tempted to make decisions that are not optimal in terms of achieving organisational objectives.\"", "\"COMMUNICATION IN BUDGETING\":\"The budgeting system facilitates communication both vertically (e.g. between senior and junior managers) and horizontally (e.g. between different organisational functions). Vertical communication enables senior managers to ensure that employees at all levels understand organisational objectives. Communication also occurs at all stages of the budgetary control process (e.g. during budget preparation and investigation of period-end variances).\"", "\"CONTROL IN BUDGETING\":\"One of the most important purposes of a budgeting system is to facilitate cost control through the comparison of budgeted costs and actual costs. Variances between budgeted and actual costs can be investigated in order to determine the reason why actual performance has differed from what was planned. Corrective action can be introduced if necessary in order to ensure that organisational objectives are achieved. A budgeting system also facilitates management by exception, whereby only significant differences between planned and actual activity are investigated.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}